Data Cleaning and Transformation

Before doing anything, we need to check if there is any missing value. We can define a function count_missing_values to do that.

count_missing_values <- function(df) {
  missing_counts <- colSums(is.na(df))
  column_names <- names(missing_counts)
  
  result <- data.frame(row.names = column_names, MissingCount = missing_counts)
  return(result)
}

Run the code, let’s see the result:

miss_ui = fluidPage(
  DT::dataTableOutput("Missing_data_counts"),
  plotOutput("plot")
)

miss_server = function(input, output) {
  output$plot <- renderPlot({
      output$Missing_data_counts = DT::renderDataTable({
        count_missing_values(global_youtube)
})
  })
}


shinyApp(ui = miss_ui, server = miss_server, options = list(height = 500))

Deal with missing data

Base on the result, we can define the missing value into different groups.

1.Remove irrelevant observation.

Some special channels like YouTube Movies, Music, Gaming, Sports, News, Popular on YouTube, Live, Minecraft - Topic are created by YouTube official. These channels don’t have any reference value. So I prefer to delete them. There are 5 observation have missing values with created_year, created_date, created_month. I prefer to delete them, too. In order not to modify any data from original file, I create a new table named clean_data to do some cleaning.

channel_names <- c("YouTube Movies", "Music", "Gaming", "Sports", "News", "Popular on YouTube", "Live", "Minecraft - Topic")

clean_data <- subset(global_youtube, !(Youtuber %in% channel_names))
clean_data <- clean_data[!is.na(clean_data$created_date), ]

So far, we removed 13 observation.

2. Imputation of Nan values

country_rank has 116 missing value. The missing value is nan means the YouTuber doesn’t select a country so the country rank is blank. There are 116 observations and it’s a remarkable number comparing with the total number. In this case, we can can treat the missing values as special values, and set missing rankings to a value different with the existing rankings number, which is “-1”. Define a function replace_value to deal with them:

replace_value <- function(df, column, value){
  df[[column]][is.na(df[[column]])] <- value
  return(df)
}

clean_data <- replace_value(clean_data, "country_rank", -1)

3. Imputation of Na values

Gross.tertiary.education.enrollment...., Population, Unemployment.rate, Urban_population, Latitude, Longitude These 6 variables have the same amount of missing values, which is 123, it’s a quite remarkable number. If we just simply remove the observations, it might be a big lost.
Analysis the dataset description and the meaning, we can see the missing values are due to a lack of country values.

For columns like Latitude and Longitude, they are real-world nature data. We can also replace them with -90 and 180. 180 longitude stands for International Date Line in the Pacific Ocean, it’s the fewest inhabitants around the world. A latitude of -90 stands for the South Pole, which is located on the continent of Antarctica. When we visualize the map using these data, we can ignore this area, no one actually lives in those areas.

Also, for Population, Unemployment.rate, Urban_population, replacing with mean values is not the best solution since it may not be accurate. So I will also use -1 to replace them.

The meaning of channel_type_rank is a rank, and sometimes it’s missing because “channel_type” is “nan”.we have 2 solution to: use the maximum value of rank plus 1 to fill it up, or use -1. In my opinion, it’s better to fill up the missing values with -1 instead of the other one. We can easily know the values are not a actual rank.

With the variables of created_year and created_date and video_views_rank, I prefer to mark up the missing values as -1 to identify they are not normal values.

4. Mean imputation

When deal with video_views_for_the_last_30_days, I reckon the video views for the last 30 days won’t be actually 0! The dataset is about the top 1000 YouTube channel, there is no point that the value will be 0. The issue could be happened when scraping the web data not correctly or just simply network error. Base on the above analysis, we can use mean values to replace them.

replace_mean <- function(df, column) {
  mean_value <- mean(df[[column]], na.rm = TRUE)
  df[[column]][is.na(df[[column]])] <- mean_value
  return(df)
}

clean_data <- replace_mean(clean_data, "video_views_for_the_last_30_days")

The same as subscribers_for_last_30_days, the reason why the value is missing is not because no one subscribes the channel, is for some reasons, it could be technical or network. But anyway, we can use mean values to fill up the missing data.

clean_data <- replace_mean(clean_data, "subscribers_for_last_30_days")

Formatting Date

we can try to put created_year, created_date, created_month together as created_time. Define a function to put them together:

parse_to_date <- function(created_year, created_month, created_date){
  data_str <- paste(created_year, created_month ,created_date, sep = '-')
  created_time <- as.Date(data_str, format = "%Y-%b-%d")
  return(created_time)
}

and then apply the function to clean_data

clean_data %>%
  mutate(created_time = 
           parse_to_date(created_year, created_month ,created_date)
         )

Logarithm transformation

For the number of highest_monthly_earnings is too large, The same thing happen to lowest_yearly_earnings and highest_yearly_earnings as well. To better describe the meaning and show their differences, and make the data more normally distributed, we can apply the logarithm transformation to this variable.

Before taking the logarithm, we need to check if there is any zero or negative data.

zero_values = clean_data[clean_data$highest_monthly_earnings <=0,]['highest_monthly_earnings']

We can see there are 89 values is or less than 0. In this case, we can try to assign these value a very small amount, like 0.01. We can define a function to calculate the log value, when the original value is or less than 0, just assign it as 0.01.

calculate_log <- function(value) {
  log_value <- ifelse(value <= 0, log(0.01), log(value))
  return(log_value)
}

And then use mutate() to add new columns, to make the code better readable, I’ll define a function apply_log_trans. I prefer to do the transformation at this stage rather than later.

apply_log_trans <- function(data, column) {
  data <- data %>%
    mutate(!!sym(column):= sapply(!!sym(column), FUN = calculate_log))
  return(data)
}

clean_data <- apply_log_trans(clean_data, "highest_monthly_earnings")
clean_data <- apply_log_trans(clean_data, "lowest_monthly_earnings")
clean_data <- apply_log_trans(clean_data, "lowest_yearly_earnings")
clean_data <- apply_log_trans(clean_data, "highest_yearly_earnings")
clean_data <- apply_log_trans(clean_data, "video.views")
clean_data <- apply_log_trans(clean_data, "subscribers")
clean_data <- apply_log_trans(clean_data, "Population")
clean_data <- apply_log_trans(clean_data, "Urban_population")
clean_data <- apply_log_trans(clean_data, "video_views_for_the_last_30_days")
clean_data <- apply_log_trans(clean_data, "Urban_population")

1. Distribution of Total Video Views

This following code defines a Shiny app that allows users to create histograms and density plots for selected variables from a clean_data based on user’s input. Users can choose a variable from the available options, adjust the bandwidth of the density plot, enter the number of histogram bins, and decide whether to add a density line to the plot.

group_hist <-c(
  "video.views",
  "highest_yearly_earnings",
  "uploads",
  "subscribers"
)

hist_ui <- fluidPage(
  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      selectInput('variable', 'Choose a variable:', choices = group_hist, selected = 'video.views'),
      sliderInput("bw", label = "Bandwidth:",
                min = 0.5, max = 1.5, value = 1, step = 0.1),
      numericInput('bins', 'Number of bins:', value = 50, min = 30),
      checkboxInput('density', 'Add density line', T)
    ),
    mainPanel(
      plotOutput('histogramPlot')
    )
  )
)

hist_server <- function(input, output) {
  output$histogramPlot <- renderPlot({
    plot <- ggplot(clean_data, aes_string(x = input$variable)) +
      geom_histogram(bins = input$bins, fill = 'grey', color = 'black', aes(y = ..density..)) +
      labs(title = paste('Histogram of', gsub('[_.]', ' ', input$variable))) +
      theme_minimal()
    if (input$density) {
      plot <- plot + geom_density(alpha = 0.2, color = 'blue', adjust = input$bw)
    }
    return(plot)
  })
}

shinyApp(ui = hist_ui, server = hist_server, options = list(height = 500))

subscribers: Only a few channels have a large number of subscribers.

2. Top Ranking

This following code defines a Shiny app that allows users to create bar plots for selected variables from a Country and category based on user’s input.

df_list = c(
  "Country",
  "category"
)

bar_ui <- fluidPage(
  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      selectInput('df_name', 'Choose a dataframe:', choices = df_list, selected = 'Country'),
      uiOutput('column_ui')
    ),
    mainPanel(
      plotOutput('barPlot')
    )
  )
)

bar_server <- function(input, output) {
  
  observe({
    df_name <- get(input$df_name)
    column_choices <- colnames(df_name)[-1]

    
    output$column_ui <- renderUI({
      selectInput('column_name', 'Choose a column:', choices = column_choices, selected = column_choices[[1]])
    })
  })
  
  output$barPlot <- renderPlot({
    df_name <- get(input$df_name)
    column_name <- input$column_name
    

    if (is.null(column_name)) return(NULL)
    df_name <- df_name[order(-df_name[[column_name]]), ]

    bar_plot <- ggplot(df_name, aes(x = reorder(df_name[[names(df_name)[1]]], -df_name[[column_name]]), y = df_name[[column_name]])) +
      geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "steelblue", alpha = 0.7) +
      theme_minimal() +
      labs(
        x = names(df_name)[1],             
        y = column_name,                   
      title = paste('Bar Plot of', gsub('[_.]', ' ', names(df_name)[1]), ' and ', column_name),
      )+
      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
      scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma)
    
    return(bar_plot)
  })
}

shinyApp(ui = bar_ui, server = bar_server, options = list(height = 500))

Base on the bar plot, The countries ranked at the top, which are India, US, Thailand, Philippines, Indonesia, Pakistan, Ukraine, United Arab Emirates, Brazil, Spain, UK have contributed the most majority of the uploads, while there are still many countries listed, creating the diversity and different culture. Channels from India have the highest number of video uploads, followed by USA and Thailand. Channels from USA have the most views andhighest annual earnings.

The United States and India are leaders in YouTube. Both countries are more outstanding than other countries in uploads , view count, and earnings. Music and Entertainment are the most popular categories.

video.views and earnings.
A positive correlation was observed between video.views and lowest_monthly_earnings, lowest_yearly_earnings, highest_monthly_earnings and highest_yearly_earnings. This means that the higher the video views, the higher the expected income range.

video.views and Population & Unemployment.rate.
The country’s population and unemployment rate do not seem to be the main factors influencing the number of videos viewed. There is also no significant relationship between video.views and Unemployment.rate, either. which suggests that unemployment may not be the main factor influencing video views.

video_views_rank and earnings.
A negative correlation was observed between video_views_rank and earnings data. This makes sense because a lower rank (i.e., 1) implies higher viewership and therefore higher expected earnings.

video_views_for_the_last_30_days and earnings.
There is a positive correlation between video views for the last 30 days and earnings data, which is consistent with our observations for video.views.

subscribers and earnings.
There is a positive correlation between the number of subscribers and the earnings data. The number of subscribers is also an important indicator of expected earnings. Channels with more subscribers tend to have higher expected earnings.

uploads and earnings.
There is no significant relationship between the number of uploads and the earnings data. This could mean that a channel’s earnings are not fully affected by the number of uploads.
